      Sonoma County PTRA Well Ordinance: A Complete Guide for Agricultural Land Buyers
    </h1>

    <!-- Byline -->
    <p style="font-size: 0.95rem; color: var(--text-light); font-style: italic; margin-bottom: 2.5rem; padding-bottom: 2rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--accent-light);">
      By Dean L. Johnson, Attorney &amp; Real Estate Broker | Sonoma Lawyers Realty
    </p>

    <!-- Article Body -->
    <div style="color: var(--text-light); line-height: 1.9; font-size: 1.05rem;">

      <p style="margin-bottom: 1.75rem;">
        If you're buying rural land, agricultural property, or a vineyard estate in Sonoma County, there's a local ordinance most buyers — and even many real estate agents — don't fully understand until it's too late. It establishes the <strong style="color: var(--text-dark);">Public Trust Review Area (PTRA)</strong>, and it sits at the heart of Sonoma County's well ordinance. For land buyers, it can be the difference between a productive property and one with severely constrained water rights.
      </p>

      <p style="margin-bottom: 2.5rem;">Here's what every buyer needs to know before making an offer.</p>

      <hr style="border: none; border-top: 1px solid var(--accent-light); margin-bottom: 2.5rem;">

      <!-- Section 1 -->
      <h2 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.8rem; color: var(--primary); margin-bottom: 1rem;">What Is the PTRA?</h2>

      <p style="margin-bottom: 1.75rem;">
        The <strong style="color: var(--text-dark);">Public Trust Review Area</strong> is a geographic zone established under <strong style="color: var(--text-dark);">Sonoma County Code Section 25B-14</strong>. It was created in response to growing concerns about groundwater depletion in the Russian River Watershed and its impact on salmon, steelhead, and other protected public trust resources.
      </p>

      <p style="margin-bottom: 2.5rem;">
        In plain terms, if a parcel sits within the PTRA boundary, and the proposed water use from a well exceeds <strong style="color: var(--text-dark);">2 acre-feet per year</strong> (roughly 651,000 gallons), the well permit is no longer a simple administrative approval. It triggers a full <strong style="color: var(--text-dark);">discretionary public trust review</strong> — a lengthier, more expensive, and less certain process.
      </p>

      <hr style="border: none; border-top: 1px solid var(--accent-light); margin-bottom: 2.5rem;">

      <!-- Section 2 -->
      <h2 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.8rem; color: var(--primary); margin-bottom: 1rem;">Why Should a Land Buyer Care?</h2>

      <p style="margin-bottom: 1.75rem;">
        Water is the most valuable resource on rural Sonoma County land. Whether you're buying a vineyard, an orchard, a lavender farm, or a large residential estate, the amount of water your well can legally produce determines what you can do with the property.
      </p>

      <p style="margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">Here's where buyers get surprised:</p>

      <!-- Key Points -->
      <div style="background: var(--cream); border-radius: 4px; padding: 2rem; margin-bottom: 2rem; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 1.5rem;">

        <div>
          <p style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--text-dark); margin-bottom: 0.4rem;">The review process takes 3 to 6 months minimum.</p>
          <p style="margin: 0;">Once triggered, the County notifies neighboring property owners within 300 feet, resource agencies, and other interested parties. A 30-day public comment period follows. Then staff analysis begins. Then written findings are issued. The permit can be approved, approved with conditions, or denied — and any denial can be appealed all the way to the Board of Supervisors.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <p style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--text-dark); margin-bottom: 0.4rem;">The review comes with a significant upfront cost.</p>
          <p style="margin: 0;">Triggering a discretionary public trust review requires a <strong style="color: var(--text-dark);">non-refundable deposit of $5,568</strong> at the time of application — and that is just the starting point. Because the fee is charged on an actual cost basis, the County will provide a preliminary estimate after initial staff review, and additional fees will be required if actual costs are expected to exceed the deposit. For complex applications involving detailed hydrogeologic studies or mitigation measures, total costs can climb well beyond the initial deposit.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <p style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--text-dark); margin-bottom: 0.4rem;">The permit can be denied.</p>
          <p style="margin: 0;">This is not a rubber-stamp process. Sonoma County can approve the well permit, approve it with conditions and mitigation measures, or deny the permit outright. For a buyer counting on agricultural water production, a denial is a serious problem.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <p style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--text-dark); margin-bottom: 0.4rem;">The legal landscape is actively shifting.</p>
          <p style="margin: 0;">The PTRA well ordinance has been at the center of ongoing litigation since 2021. The most recent chapter began when Sonoma County Superior Court Judge Bradford DeMeo ruled in August 2024 that the County's 2023 Amended Well Ordinance violated CEQA and inadequately addressed its Public Trust obligations. The Court ordered the County to suspend all non-emergency well permitting and void the Amended Ordinance pending a full environmental review.</p>
        </div>

      </div>

      <p style="margin-bottom: 1.75rem;">
        The County was served with the formal Judgment on December 17, 2024, and immediately halted permits. After a period of emergency motions and short-term stipulated stays, the First District Court of Appeal granted Sonoma County a temporary stay on March 27, 2025, allowing the County to resume issuing non-emergency well permits while it appeals the ruling. The County filed its Opening Brief in October 2025. The appeal remains pending as of this writing.
      </p>

      <p style="margin-bottom: 2.5rem;">
        For buyers, the practical takeaway is this: permits are currently being issued under the 2023 Amended Ordinance and PTRA review requirements remain in effect. But the appellate stay is temporary. If the County loses on appeal, the Amended Ordinance would be invalidated and permitting could halt again — potentially for years — while a CEQA-compliant replacement is developed. Buyers of agricultural or well-dependent property should treat this litigation as a material risk and work with counsel who can monitor its status in real time.
      </p>

      <hr style="border: none; border-top: 1px solid var(--accent-light); margin-bottom: 2.5rem;">

      <!-- Section 3 -->
      <h2 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.8rem; color: var(--primary); margin-bottom: 1rem;">What Triggers the Full Review?</h2>

      <p style="margin-bottom: 1.75rem;">
        Discretionary Public Trust Review is required when all three of the following are true: groundwater use will be increasing, total groundwater use of the parcel will exceed <strong style="color: var(--text-dark);">2 acre-feet per year</strong>, and the well is located within the Public Trust Review Area.
      </p>

      <p style="margin-bottom: 1.75rem;">
        For agricultural land, that threshold is easy to exceed. Vineyard and orchard irrigation alone is limited to <strong style="color: var(--text-dark);">0.6 acre-feet per year per acre</strong> under conservation requirements — meaning even a modest 4-acre irrigated vineyard approaches the review threshold on its own.
      </p>

      <p style="margin-bottom: 2.5rem;">
        Some wells are exempt from full discretionary review, but staff must review each permit application individually to determine whether the proposed well falls within one of the exemptions. You cannot assume exemption applies without verification.
      </p>

      <hr style="border: none; border-top: 1px solid var(--accent-light); margin-bottom: 2.5rem;">

      <!-- Section 4 -->
      <h2 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.8rem; color: var(--primary); margin-bottom: 1rem;">What Does This Mean for Your Due Diligence?</h2>

      <p style="margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">If you're purchasing land in Sonoma County — especially anything agricultural — your due diligence checklist must include:</p>

      <ol style="padding-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 2.5rem; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 1rem;">
        <li><strong style="color: var(--text-dark);">Is the parcel within the PTRA boundary?</strong> Check the Sonoma Well Ordinance Online Map before making an offer.</li>
        <li><strong style="color: var(--text-dark);">What is the current well's permitted use and capacity?</strong> Existing wells carry their own permit history and limitations.</li>
        <li><strong style="color: var(--text-dark);">Does your intended use exceed 2 acre-feet per year?</strong> If yes, and you're in the PTRA, plan for a costly and lengthy permitting process.</li>
        <li><strong style="color: var(--text-dark);">Are there any pending or proposed changes to the well ordinance?</strong> Given the active litigation, the rules could tighten even further.</li>
      </ol>

      <hr style="border: none; border-top: 1px solid var(--accent-light); margin-bottom: 2.5rem;">

      <!-- Section 5 -->
      <h2 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.8rem; color: var(--primary); margin-bottom: 1rem;">Why This Is Exactly Where a Buyer's Agent Who Is Also an Attorney Makes a Difference</h2>

      <p style="margin-bottom: 1.75rem;">
        Most real estate agents will tell you to "check with the county" on water. That's not enough. A buyer purchasing agricultural land in Sonoma County needs someone who can actually read and interpret Sonoma County Code Chapter 25B, understand the legal implications of the ongoing public trust litigation, identify PTRA exposure before escrow opens, and negotiate contract contingencies that protect you if water rights don't pencil out.
      </p>

      <p style="margin-bottom: 1.75rem;">
